Veeshan Server</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ufiremynd.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Firemynd</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(5/28/02 2:44:21 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovegeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=27426.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: DS or Slow: Which is better?</span><hr size=1> &quot;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> I have also long thought that it was highly ironic that slow works against DS... </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->&quot;<br>
<br>
I don't think one spell diminishing the other's effectiveness was VI's original intent with these two lines of spells. Rather, I believe VI intended for shamans and druids to each possess own ways to mitigate damage -- to compensate for having secondary healing ability. <br>
<br>
This type of mitigation can be seen across the spectrum. <br>
<br>
Take secondary defensive classes, for example. Paladins have less raw ability to tank than a warrior has, but they are able to cast stuns which help to mitigate the overall amount of damage taken. Shadowknights have less raw ability to taunt, but they can use lifetap and debuff spells to keep or regain a mob's attention.<br>
<br>
The problem is, VI has based the high-end game too much upon a very few specialist abilities; maybe because it was easier and quicker to use lowest common denominators, or perhaps they didn't anticipate how scientific players can be when it comes to developing strategies (&quot;show me some numbers or shut the $%@&amp; up&quot;), nor how rarely its players will stray from a proven stratagem. <br>
<br>
It isn't VI's fault that players crunch numbers and determine the most efficient methods to take down each type of mob, but IMO, it was VI's responsibility to know their player base well enough to realize that people suspend any sense of abstract roleplay when it comes to phat lewt. And therefore it was VI's responsibility to take all classes into consideration when developing high-end encounters.<br>
<br>
While I think it should have come at a much later level than 39, CH itself doesn't break the game. On the contrary, ever since CH was introduced into the game, it has been one of those LCDs (lowest common denominators) VI has used when developing nearly all of its new higher level content. To remove CH from the game at this point would break many encounters; and frankly, even if they wanted to, I doubt they could go back and redesign all that content. So, realistically, removing CH is impossible.<br>
<br>
Because it is futile (i.e. waste of effort) to ask for the impossible, those who play classes which were left out of VI's equation need to help VI see the need to add class abilities that can be significant to those LCD encounters. <br>
<br>
My suggestion for new types of DS is an example of this; I explained how the concept of DS had become broken over time, and proposed how it could be fixed, relative to a similar mitigating ability (shaman slow) that scales up/down with mobs. <br>
<br>
I could think of a dozen DS types that would provide druids with a new effectiveness in raiding without overbalancing existing encounters, but it's probably best to stop at the initial idea and let VI take it from there. Give them a direction without making them feel they're being dictated any specifics.<br>
<br>
~Firemynd  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/usorrun.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Sorrun</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(5/28/02 2:57:07 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovegeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=27426.topic&index=28>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ...</span><hr size=1> First of all, I recall CH being the CAUSE of many high end encounters being so difficult.  Assuming that is correct, that is the only reason it has evolved past the point of being as useful... sort of a cart and horse question more then anything else.  I have always viewed CH has the horse and the cart as the difficulty of high end encounters.<br>
<br>
A percentage based DS would probably require Sony to raise the bar on high end encounters similar to how CH raised the bar.  As long as everyone realizes this and accepts it as a very possible consquence, so be it.  I definately think this is the lesser evil of all the options I have seen so far.  Not a great idea, but probably the best of the ones to choose from.<br>
<br>
/devil's advocate on<br>
<br>
It is fair to assume Sony would give mages the same DS spells, just fire based... therefore would mages just take over this abilitiy in raids since thier dmg shields are already superior to druids?<br>
<br>
/devil's advocate off<br>
<br>
One positive (depending on your perspective) would be that it would be easier to load up a good DS on your twink and not have the shield steal the kill... :)<br>
