<br>
If the intent was to provide druids and shaman with ways to avoid melee damage in order to compensate for lesser healing, it is obvious shaman got the far supeior end of the stick.  Aside from its obvious superior mana/dmg ratio, druid (and mage for that matter) damage shields become less and less useful as one gets closer to 60 simply due to the high number of HP's you find on those mobs.  Sure, you still enjoy a great ratio, but the contribution the DS makes to the battle is often times not noticable and definately not ground breaking... slow on the other hand seems to become more and more effective as shaman level.<br>
<br>
I am not sure why this just popped into my head.. maybe I read it in some thread, maybe not.  How about adding a small resist component to damage shields and then making them percentage based.  Either a normal initial resistance check at the first hit that effected all subsequent hits or a very minor resistance check for each hit with partial or no damage being the result of a successful resistance check.  That could serve to easily balance the power of percentage based dmg shields. <p><table border="0">
